==English==
===Etymology===
From '''[[pale]]''', a region held by one nation in another country; hence suggesting that anything outside their control was uncivilised. It was in use by the mid-17th century. The phrase is a reference to the general sense of boundary, not to any of the particular places, such as the English [[Pale]] in Ireland, which bore that name. Out of the many districts established by England, only a select few followed the laws established by England, Hence [[within the Pale]] and [[beyond the pale]].
